Founded in 1997, the company was previously owned by Cegedim (a global healthcare technology company) before being acquired by N. Harris Computer Corporation in September 2019. Pulse now operates within the **Harris Ambulatory Care Enterprise** family alongside several other ambulatory EHR products including Amazing Charts, PrognoCIS, CareTracker, GEMMS, digiChart, and Picasso EHR. The developer contact email (@harriscomputer.com) confirms this corporate relationship.\n     9→\n    10→Pulse claims to have \"worked with thousands of providers\" across a variety of specialties. The product targets ambulatory practices of all sizes, including solo practices, multi-site groups, ambulatory surgical centers, integrated delivery networks (IDNs), and management services organizations (MSOs). The vendor emphasizes customizable workflows tailored to individual practice needs. Pulse is a Surescripts Gold Solution Provider (awarded five consecutive years per their press materials), indicating strong e-prescribing integration.\n    11→\n    12→## Product: Pulse EHR\n    13→\n    14→CHPL ID: 11500\n    15→\n    16→### What It Is\n    17→\n    18→Pulse EHR is an integrated electronic health records and practice management platform marketed as \"Pulse EHR/PM.\" The certified product (version 8.02, certified 2024-08-06) carries a broad set of ONC certifications spanning clinical data management (a)(1)–(a)(5), (a)(12), (a)(14), transitions of care (b)(1)–(b)(3), clinical quality measures (c)(1), public health reporting (f)(1),(f)(3),(f)(5), FHIR APIs (g)(7),(g)(10), and direct messaging (h)(1). This breadth indicates a full-featured clinical EHR, not a narrow specialty module.\n    19→\n    20→The certified module appears to be the core of the product — the vendor markets Pulse EHR, PulsePro (practice management), PulseRCM (revenue cycle management), and Population Health as an integrated suite, but the EHR/PM components are tightly coupled. The SED intended user description is \"Providers, clinical users, support staff,\" confirming ambulatory clinical and administrative users.\n    21→\n    22→### Users & Market\n    23→\n    24→- **Settings**: Ambulatory practices across multiple specialties. The vendor website highlights case studies in urology, gastroenterology, and orthopedics. Third-party review sites list supported specialties as primary care, FQHCs, community health, rural clinics, behavioral health, pediatrics, cardiology, neurology, oncology, and orthopedics.\n    25→- **Practice sizes**: Solo practices to multi-site groups, ASCs, IDNs, and MSOs.\n    26→- **Scale**: \"Thousands of providers\" — exact numbers not disclosed. The product appears to be a small-to-mid-market ambulatory EHR, not a large enterprise system.\n    27→- **Deployment**: Cloud-based or server-based options available.\n    28→- **Reviews**: Very limited review presence — Software Advice and FindEMR list the product but with only ~2 user reviews. One user praised ease of navigation and seamless PM/EHR integration; another noted \"too many clicks or duplicate modules\" during training. A 95% satisfaction rating is claimed but based on a very small sample.\n    29→\n    30→### Modules & Functionality\n    31→\n    32→Based on vendor website descriptions, review sites, and certification criteria:\n    33→\n    34→**Clinical Documentation (EHR)**\n    35→- Customizable flow sheets configurable per provider\n    36→- \"Pulse Note\" — described as an \"Advanced Clinical Knowledge Engine\" for clinical intelligence\n    37→- Patient Clinical Snapshot (PCS) — consolidated patient overview\n    38→- Multiple problem visit templates for various encounter types\n    39→- Point-of-care charting with E&M code checking\n    40→- Evaluation & Management (E&M) coder for documentation accuracy\n    41→\n    42→**Computerized Provider Order Entry (CPOE)**\n    43→- Medication ordering with drug interaction checking\n    44→- Laboratory order entry\n    45→- Diagnostic imaging order entry\n    46→\n    47→**E-Prescribing**\n    48→- Surescripts Gold Solution Provider\n    49→- Electronic prescribing functionality (costs listed as one-time and ongoing fees on mandatory disclosures page)\n    50→- EPCS capability implied by Surescripts integration but not explicitly confirmed on vendor site\n    51→\n    52→**Practice Management (PulsePro)**\n    53→- Advanced scheduling and patient registration\n    54→- Medical billing, coding, and claims processing\n    55→- Insurance eligibility verification (individual or batch mode)\n    56→- Automated workflow lists for task management\n    57→- A/R tracking and management\n    58→- Payment posting, claim appeals, payment reconciliation, denial refiling\n    59→- Proprietary analytics and reporting\n    60→\n    61→**Revenue Cycle Management (PulseRCM)**\n    62→- Claims management with 98% first-pass clean claims rate (per vendor)\n    63→- Certified coding support\n    64→- Denial management and root cause analysis\n    65→- Can be technology-only or bundled with managed services\n    66→\n    67→**Patient Engagement**\n    68→- Patient portal via InteliChart partnership — provides 24/7 secure access to health records, lab/diagnostic results, educational materials, and discharge instructions (monthly fees apply per mandatory disclosures)\n    69→- Pulse Engage — automated, integrated patient reminder system for appointments\n    70→\n    71→**Population Health**\n    72→- Clinical Quality Measures (CQM) module — tracks and submits quality data to CMS\n    73→- Care gaps identification and remediation\n    74→- Patient View feature for pre-visit review\n    75→- Chronic Care Management module\n    76→- Practice-wide analytics (risk stratification, quality measurement, performance tracking)\n    77→- MACRA/MIPS qualification support\n    78→- Qualified CMS Registry for PQRS incentives\n    79→\n    80→**Document Management**\n    81→- Integrated document, fax, and transcription management\n    82→- Voice-to-text transcription capabilities\n    83→\n    84→**Public Health Reporting**\n    85→- Immunization registry reporting — certified (f)(1)\n    86→- Electronic case reporting — certified (f)(3)\n    87→- Electronic reportable lab results — certified (f)(5)\n    88→\n    89→**Interoperability**\n    90→- Transitions of care / C-CDA exchange — certified (b)(1)–(b)(3)\n    91→- Direct secure messaging — certified (h)(1)\n    92→- FHIR-based APIs for patient and population services — certified (g)(7),(g)(10)\n    93→- EHI export — certified (b)(10)\n    94→- Lab integration (results automatically attached to patient records)\n    95→\n    96→### Data & Content\n    97→\n    98→Based on the features and certifications described above, the product manages:\n    99→\n   100→- **Patient demographics and registration data** — eligibility verification feature\n   113→- **Quality measure data** — CQM module, MIPS/MACRA reporting\n   114→- **Patient portal messages and shared records** — InteliChart integration\n   115→- **Faxes, transcriptions, and scanned documents** — integrated document management\n   116→- **Care plan and care gap data** — population health module\n   117→- **Audit logs and access records** — certified (d) criteria for security\n   118→- **Immunization records** — public health reporting certified\n   119→- **Clinical decision support rules** — certified (a)(14)\n   120→\n   121→**Data gaps / uncertainties:**\n   122→- The vendor website does not explicitly mention **referral management** as a distinct module, though transitions of care certification implies some referral tracking capability.\n   123→- No mention of **telehealth/virtual visit** capabilities on the Pulse website, though the broader Harris Ambulatory group offers \"virtual care solutions.\"\n   124→- **Secure messaging between providers** (beyond Direct) is not explicitly described — unclear whether the system supports internal messaging workflows.\n   125→- The distinction between data stored in Pulse EHR vs. data managed solely within the InteliChart patient portal is unclear — the portal is a third-party integration, so portal-specific data (patient-entered information, message threads) may reside partially outside the Pulse system.\n   126→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. Founded in 1997, the company was previously owned by Cegedim (a global healthcare technology company) before being acquired by N. Harris Computer Corporation in September 2019. Pulse now operates within the **Harris Ambulatory Care Enterprise** family alongside several other ambulatory EHR products including Amazing Charts, PrognoCIS, CareTracker, GEMMS, digiChart, and Picasso EHR. The developer contact email (@harriscomputer.com) confirms this corporate relationship.\n\nPulse claims to have \"worked with thousands of providers\" across a variety of specialties. The product targets ambulatory practices of all sizes, including solo practices, multi-site groups, ambulatory surgical centers, integrated delivery networks (IDNs), and management services organizations (MSOs). The vendor emphasizes customizable workflows tailored to individual practice needs. Pulse is a Surescripts Gold Solution Provider (awarded five consecutive years per their press materials), indicating strong e-prescribing integration.\n\n## Product: Pulse EHR\n\nCHPL ID: 11500\n\n### What It Is\n\nPulse EHR is an integrated electronic health records and practice management platform marketed as \"Pulse EHR/PM.\" The certified product (version 8.02, certified 2024-08-06) carries a broad set of ONC certifications spanning clinical data management (a)(1)–(a)(5), (a)(12), (a)(14), transitions of care (b)(1)–(b)(3), clinical quality measures (c)(1), public health reporting (f)(1),(f)(3),(f)(5), FHIR APIs (g)(7),(g)(10), and direct messaging (h)(1). This breadth indicates a full-featured clinical EHR, not a narrow specialty module.\n\nThe certified module appears to be the core of the product — the vendor markets Pulse EHR, PulsePro (practice management), PulseRCM (revenue cycle management), and Population Health as an integrated suite, but the EHR/PM components are tightly coupled. The SED intended user description is \"Providers, clinical users, support staff,\" confirming ambulatory clinical and administrative users.\n\n### Users & Market\n\n- **Settings**: Ambulatory practices across multiple specialties. The vendor website highlights case studies in urology, gastroenterology, and orthopedics. Third-party review sites list supported specialties as primary care, FQHCs, community health, rural clinics, behavioral health, pediatrics, cardiology, neurology, oncology, and orthopedics.\n- **Practice sizes**: Solo practices to multi-site groups, ASCs, IDNs, and MSOs.\n- **Scale**: \"Thousands of providers\" — exact numbers not disclosed. The product appears to be a small-to-mid-market ambulatory EHR, not a large enterprise system.\n- **Deployment**: Cloud-based or server-based options available.\n- **Reviews**: Very limited review presence — Software Advice and FindEMR list the product but with only ~2 user reviews. One user praised ease of navigation and seamless PM/EHR integration; another noted \"too many clicks or duplicate modules\" during training. A 95% satisfaction rating is claimed but based on a very small sample.\n\n### Modules & Functionality\n\nBased on vendor website descriptions, review sites, and certification criteria:\n\n**Clinical Documentation (EHR)**\n- Customizable flow sheets configurable per provider\n- \"Pulse Note\" — described as an \"Advanced Clinical Knowledge Engine\" for clinical intelligence\n- Patient Clinical Snapshot (PCS) — consolidated patient overview\n- Multiple problem visit templates for various encounter types\n- Point-of-care charting with E&M code checking\n- Evaluation & Management (E&M) coder for documentation accuracy\n\n**Computerized Provider Order Entry (CPOE)**\n- Medication ordering with drug interaction checking\n- Laboratory order entry\n- Diagnostic imaging order entry\n\n**E-Prescribing**\n- Surescripts Gold Solution Provider\n- Electronic prescribing functionality (costs listed as one-time and ongoing fees on mandatory disclosures page)\n- EPCS capability implied by Surescripts integration but not explicitly confirmed on vendor site\n\n**Practice Management (PulsePro)**\n- Advanced scheduling and patient registration\n- Medical billing, coding, and claims processing\n- Insurance eligibility verification (individual or batch mode)\n- Automated workflow lists for task management\n- A/R tracking and management\n- Payment posting, claim appeals, payment reconciliation, denial refiling\n- Proprietary analytics and reporting\n\n**Revenue Cycle Management (PulseRCM)**\n- Claims management with 98% first-pass clean claims rate (per vendor)\n- Certified coding support\n- Denial management and root cause analysis\n- Can be technology-only or bundled with managed services\n\n**Patient Engagement**\n- Patient portal via InteliChart partnership — provides 24/7 secure access to health records, lab/diagnostic results, educational materials, and discharge instructions (monthly fees apply per mandatory disclosures)\n- Pulse Engage — automated, integrated patient reminder system for appointments\n\n**Population Health**\n- Clinical Quality Measures (CQM) module — tracks and submits quality data to CMS\n- Care gaps identification and remediation\n- Patient View feature for pre-visit review\n- Chronic Care Management module\n- Practice-wide analytics (risk stratification, quality measurement, performance tracking)\n- MACRA/MIPS qualification support\n- Qualified CMS Registry for PQRS incentives\n\n**Document Management**\n- Integrated document, fax, and transcription management\n- Voice-to-text transcription capabilities\n\n**Public Health Reporting**\n- Immunization registry reporting — certified (f)(1)\n- Electronic case reporting — certified (f)(3)\n- Electronic reportable lab results — certified (f)(5)\n\n**Interoperability**\n- Transitions of care / C-CDA exchange — certified (b)(1)–(b)(3)\n- Direct secure messaging — certified (h)(1)\n- FHIR-based APIs for patient and population services — certified (g)(7),(g)(10)\n- EHI export — certified (b)(10)\n- Lab integration (results automatically attached to patient records)\n\n### Data & Content\n\nBased on the features and certifications described above, the product manages:\n\n- **Patient demographics and registration data** — core PM function\n- **Clinical notes and encounter documentation** — flow sheets, templates, Pulse Note engine\n- **Medication lists and prescription history** — CPOE and e-prescribing via Surescripts\n- **Laboratory orders and results** — CPOE and lab integration\n- **Diagnostic imaging orders** — CPOE certified\n- **Vital signs and clinical measurements** — documented in review sites\n- **Problem lists and diagnoses** — multiple problem visit templates\n- **Family health history** — listed in mandatory disclosures certification criteria\n- **Implantable device data** — listed in mandatory disclosures\n- **Allergies/drug interactions** — drug interaction checking is a certified feature\n- **Scheduling and appointment data** — PulsePro scheduling module\n- **Billing, claims, and financial data** — PulsePro billing/coding, PulseRCM claims management\n- **Insurance eligibility and payer data** — eligibility verification feature\n- **Quality measure data** — CQM module, MIPS/MACRA reporting\n- **Patient portal messages and shared records** — InteliChart integration\n- **Faxes, transcriptions, and scanned documents** — integrated document management\n- **Care plan and care gap data** — population health module\n- **Audit logs and access records** — certified (d) criteria for security\n- **Immunization records** — public health reporting certified\n- **Clinical decision support rules** — certified (a)(14)\n\n**Data gaps / uncertainties:**\n- The vendor website does not explicitly mention **referral management** as a distinct module, though transitions of care certification implies some referral tracking capability.\n- No mention of **telehealth/virtual visit** capabilities on the Pulse website, though the broader Harris Ambulatory group offers \"virtual care solutions.\"\n- **Secure messaging between providers** (beyond Direct) is not explicitly described — unclear whether the system supports internal messaging workflows.\n- The distinction between data stored in Pulse EHR vs. data managed solely within the InteliChart patient portal is unclear — the portal is a third-party integration, so portal-specific data (patient-entered information, message threads) may reside partially outside the Pulse system.\n","numLines":126,"startLine":1,"totalLines":126}}}

It uses\nAuthentication Server 3 which implements a Patient Token system to provide a high\nlevel of security.\n\n2 Starting Your Implementation\n2.1 REST and JSON\nREST (REpresentational State Transfer) is a web service architectural style. In general\nit means that aspects of the HTTP protocol are used to retrieve or manipulate data from\na remote system. As with HTTP, a RESTful API is called with the combination of a URL\nand a verb. The verb indicates the type of action that is requested.\nThe API only utilizes the POST verb for all operations.\nJSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a notation style used to represent complex object\nstructures in a serialized manner (i.e. transferable over the Internet). It has a similar\nrole to XML but is much less verbose and therefore faster. All request and response\nmessages will be JSON messages.\n2.2 Security\nThe call to PulseAuthenticationtoken will return a token, and it will be used for all\nsubsequent data requests for that session.\nSSL is used for transport security. The SSL protocol runs above TCP/IP and below\nhigher-level protocols such as HTTP. It uses TCP/IP on behalf of the higher-level\nprotocols, and in the process allows an SSL-enabled server to authenticate itself to and\nSSL-enabled clients, allows the client to authenticate itself to the server, and allows\nboth machines to establish an encrypted connection.\nAn encrypted SSL connection requires all information sent between a client and a\nserver to be encrypted by the sending software and decrypted by the receiving\nsoftware, thus providing a high degree of confidentiality. This is important for both\nparties to any private transaction. In addition, all data sent over an encrypted SSL\nImplementation Guide (v1.0)\nPage 4 of 10\n\n\fPulse\nconnection is protected with a mechanism for detecting tampering (i.e. for automatically\ndetermining whether the data has been altered in transit).\n\n3 Implementation Support\n\nAs the developer, you are not limited to any particular technology to access The API.\nFor the purposes of this Implementation Guide, Postman will be used in all the\nexamples.\n\n3.1 The API Access Workflow\n\nAccessing The API is a multi-step process (refer to Figure 1). The API only utilizes the\nPOST verb for all operations.\nThe first step is to request an authorization token from the authentication server that will\nbe included in all subsequent requests. The credentials needed to obtain the\nAuthorization Token will be provided by the practice. An example of this step is shown\nin section (3.1.1 Authentication Token).\nThe next step is to send a request message (with the Authorization Token) that contains\nthe Patient Identifiers, a start date, and end date to the endpoint (related to the data\nbeing requested) on the application server. The application server will then validate the\nAuthorization Token If valid, the application server will return the data to the client.\nExamples of this step are shown in sections (3.2.2).\nThe Authorization Token has a time to live (TTL) of 60 minutes. There is no harm in\nalways starting the process from Step 1 for every endpoint request.\nAppendix B: Status Codes and Messages lists all status codes and status messages\nthat may be return by The API.\n3.1.1 Authentication Token\nAuthorization Endpoint Address:\nhttps://localhost\nAccess Token Endpoint Address:\nhttps://localhost //PulseAuthenticationToken/token/generate\nHere is an example of requesting an Authorization Token from the authentication Server using\nPostman:\n\nImplementation Guide (v1.0)\nPage 5 of 10\n\n\fPulse\n\nThe basic creds will be provided by the practice. Once the Authorization Token has\nbeen received from the server, it must be used in all subsequent requests. The token is\nto be included in the header of the messages. For example:\n\nImplementation Guide (v1.0)\nPage 6 of 10\n\n\fPulse\n\n3.2 The API Endpoint Example\n3.2.1 CCD Download\nEndpoint Address:\nhttps://localhost/pulseunifiedapiToken/api/EXECUTE","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d65e0b77-4a97-43d8-b0ff-f4d1956a9a56","uuid":"775e4a49-b2dc-4bfc-88e9-6de630948f24","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Pulse\n\nPulse Common Clinical Data API\nImplementation Guide\nVersion 1.0\n11/21/2022\n\n\fPulse\nVERSION HISTORY\nVersion\n#\n\n1.0\n\nImplemented\nBy\n\nRob Sprague\n\nRevision\nDate\n\n11/21/2022\n\nApproved\nBy\n\nApproval\nDate\n\nReason\n\nOriginal Draft\n\nImplementation Guide (v1.0)\nPage 2 of 10\n\n\fPulse\nTable of Contents\n1\n\nIntroduction ........................................................................................................................... 4\n\n1.1\nWHO IS THIS DOCUMENT FOR? In general\nit means that aspects of the HTTP protocol are used to retrieve or manipulate data from\na remote system. As with HTTP, a RESTful API is called with the combination of a URL\nand a verb. The verb indicates the type of action that is requested.\nThe API only utilizes the POST verb for all operations.\nJSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a notation style used to represent complex object\nstructures in a serialized manner (i.e. transferable over the Internet). It has a similar\nrole to XML but is much less verbose and therefore faster. All request and response\nmessages will be JSON messages.\n2.2 Security\nThe call to PulseAuthenticationtoken will return a token, and it will be used for all\nsubsequent data requests for that session.\nSSL is used for transport security. The SSL protocol runs above TCP/IP and below\nhigher-level protocols such as HTTP. It uses TCP/IP on behalf of the higher-level\nprotocols, and in the process allows an SSL-enabled server to authenticate itself to and\nSSL-enabled clients, allows the client to authenticate itself to the server, and allows\nboth machines to establish an encrypted connection.\nAn encrypted SSL connection requires all information sent between a client and a\nserver to be encrypted by the sending software and decrypted by the receiving\nsoftware, thus providing a high degree of confidentiality. This is important for both\nparties to any private transaction. In addition, all data sent over an encrypted SSL\nImplementation Guide (v1.0)\nPage 4 of 10\n\n\fPulse\nconnection is protected with a mechanism for detecting tampering (i.e. for automatically\ndetermining whether the data has been altered in transit).\n\n3 Implementation Support\n\nAs the developer, you are not limited to any particular technology to access The API.\nFor the purposes of this Implementation Guide, Postman will be used in all the\nexamples.\n\n3.1 The API Access Workflow\n\nAccessing The API is a multi-step process (refer to Figure 1). The API only utilizes the\nPOST verb for all operations.\nThe first step is to request an authorization token from the authentication server that will\nbe included in all subsequent requests. The credentials needed to obtain the\nAuthorization Token will be provided by the practice. An example of this step is shown\nin section (3.1.1 Authentication Token).\nThe next step is to send a request message (with the Authorization Token) that contains\nthe Patient Identifiers, a start date, and end date to the endpoint (related to the data\nbeing requested) on the application server. The application server will then validate the\nAuthorization Token If valid, the application server will return the data to the client.\nExamples of this step are shown in sections (3.2.2).\nThe Authorization Token has a time to live (TTL) of 60 minutes. There is no harm in\nalways starting the process from Step 1 for every endpoint request.\nAppendix B: Status Codes and Messages lists all status codes and status messages\nthat may be return by The API.\n3.1.1 Authentication Token\nAuthorization Endpoint Address:\nhttps://localhost\nAccess Token Endpoint Address:\nhttps://localhost //PulseAuthenticationToken/token/generate\nHere is an example of requesting an Authorization Token from the authentication Server using\nPostman:\n\nImplementation Guide (v1.0)\nPage 5 of 10\n\n\fPulse\n\nThe basic creds will be provided by the practice. Your application will need to\nre-authenticate, using the Get Token method.\nResponse = System.Argument Exception\n• This is an indication that you are not passing the 4\nrequired arguments. PersonNo, FamilyNo, StartDate,\nEndDate\n• If you want an all encompassing CCD, please pass a\ndate range that will include all the data you want. IE,\n1900-1-1 to 2050-1-1\nDecoded Bytes value is “No encounter data was found; empty\nCCD will not be generated”\n• This is an indication that you have provided a date range\nfor the patient, where no encounter was found.\nEncounter data is required to build the CCD. Please\nalter your date range.\nResponse values are blank, and/or null Bytes value\n• This is an indication that the FamilyNo/PersonNo is not\naccurate.\nInternal Server Error\n\nImplementation Guide (v1.0)\nPage 10 of 10","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false}}

Pulse §170.315(G)(10) FHIR API Documentation Click here to view Registration Developers wishing to integrate with the API must contact the PHI Provider that uses Pulse as their EMR. Pulse is an On-Prem EMR solution and as such, each API instance is separate based on the Provider (each Provider is considered a separate entity and will have their own API URL, registration for which third-party developers have access to their data via the FHIR API on their system, and each Provider is responsible for maintaining the rights of API accounts). Once a Provider decides to grant access to you as a third-party developer, they will set up a new developer account with access to the API based on the needs of the developer and agreed upon permissions with the Provider. Pricing The fees outlined below are applicable to the 3 rd party application developer/vendors and individual practice (end users) whose objective is to interface and extract patient information using FHIR APIs to be provided to patients requesting personal electronic health information.                                                                    API Developer/Vendor Pulse End User (Practice) ONC 2015 Edition Certified API License $2500 No additional charge &#8211; included in active support agreement Integration Assistance, Implementation, Testing, Education and Ongoing Support Hourly at standard billable rates ($175/hour) &#8211; minimum 8 hours No additional charge &#8211; included in active support agreement For more information, please complete the following: https://harrisambulatory.com/contact-us/ Let's talk! US Core ImplantableDevice Profile ............ 33\nLocation .......................................................................................................................... 35\nOrganization USCore Organization Profile ...................................................................... 36\nPractitioner USCore Practitioner Profile. ........................................................................ 37\nVital Signs – FHIR Core VitalSigns Profile ........................................................................ 38\nQuery for All Data as a CCDA document ......................................................................... 40\nQuery for a Specific Date or Date Range ......................................................................... 41\n\n2\n\n\fIntroduction:\nThis document describers the Integration with the SMART App Launch Framework via FHIR allows a thirdparty application to connect with Provider(s) using the Pulse Software and retrieve Electronic Health\nRecord data from those Providers.\nThis API collection for use of Health IT developers seeking to use our ONC 2015 Edition Cures Update\nCertified (g)(10) Standardized API for Health Level 7 (HL7®) Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources\n(FHIR®) services.\nThese applications can launch from inside or outside the user interface of Pulse. The framework supports\nApps for use by clinicians, patients, and others via a Patient Portal or any FHIR system where a user can\ngive permissions to launch an App. It provides a reliable, secure authorization protocol for a variety of App\narchitectures, including Apps that run on an end-user’s device as well as Apps that run on a secure server.\nThis documentation is intended for use by third-party application developers which will describe\nregistration, syntax, functionality and errors/exceptions they will see when using the FHIR API to integrate\nwith provider(s) using the Pulse software\nRegistration\nDevelopers wishing to integrate with the API must contact the PHI Provider that uses Pulse as their EMR.\nPulse is an On-Prem EMR solution and as such, each API instance is separate based on the Provider (each\nProvider is considered a separate entity and will have their own API URL, registration for which third-party\ndevelopers have access to their data via the FHIR API on their system, and each Provider is responsible for\nmaintaining the rights of API accounts). Once a Provider decides to grant access to you as a third-party\ndeveloper, they will set up a new developer account with access to the API based on the needs of the\ndeveloper and agreed upon permissions with the Provider.\nConfigurations\nThe following are configuration settings that a third-party developer App needs to meet:\n1 The App MUST read and parse JSON responses.\n2 The App MUST assure that sensitive information (authentication secrets, authorization codes,\ntokens) are transmitted ONLY to authenticated servers, over TLS-secured channels.\n§170.315(g)(10) requires secure connection using TLS version 1.2 or higher.\n3 If the App is a Bulk Export application, the application MAY need to be setup to handle longer\nlasting connections based on the data that is being exported.\n4 The App MUST send requests over HTTPS. HTTP requests will be rejected.\nIt is published on the endpoint: https://hag-fhir.amazingcharts.com/pl/endpoints\n\n3\n\n\fAPI Resources:\nAPI Resource response can be requested in JSON or XML format.\nFHIR standard R4\n\n4\n\n\fALLERGIES AND INTOLERANCES US CORE ALLERGYINTOLERANCE PROFILEUS Core AllergyIntolerance Profile\nUSCore Data Element\n\nFHIR Resource Field\n\nSubstance(Drug class)\n\nAllergyIntolerance.code(Snomed CT)\n\nSubstance(Medication)\n\nAllergyIntolerance.code (RxNorm)\n\nReaction\n\nAllergyIntolerance.reaction\n\nAllergy Intolerance\nFor an example JSON response for Allergy Intolerance, please see the following: AllergyIntolerance.\nThis resource is called like the following (with no parameters):\nGET https://FHIR_URL/AllergyIntolerance\nAuthorization: Bearer sntumgwar8ffwrama.hhgtf823.dlfjhimmakegbngwu","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d65e0b77-4a97-43d8-b0ff-f4d1956a9a56","uuid":"26e498b1-ae70-4aaf-a07f-5f423d3e192b","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Pulse\n§170.315(G)(10) FHIR API\nDocumentation\n\nVersion 8.0\nOctober 31, 2022\nPulse 8.0 API FHIR Documentation.docx\n1\n\n\fTABLE OF CONTENTS\nTable of Contents.............................................................................................................. 2\nIntroduction ...................................................................................................................... 3\nAPI Resources ................................................................................................................... 4\nAllergies and Intolerances US core AllergyIntolerance Profile .......................................... 5\nAssessment and Plan of Treatment - Some electronic health information might not be available in a format, such as rich text documents or images. \nThe content included in the export might vary based on a variety of factors, including:\n    • The software applications in use at the health system that generated the files.\n    • The documentation and software use practices in place at the health system that generated the files.\n    • Configuration decisions made by the health system that generated the files.\nFor a standards-based way of exchanging health information, we recommend reviewing the following. \nThis PULSE EHI information will be available https://www.chs.net/pulse-ehr-information/ \nClinical Document Architecture (CDA) \nWhen exchanging patient summary documents, we use Clinical Document Architecture (CDA) as the content standard. CDA is an XML-based markup standard defined by Health Level Seven (HL7), intended to specify encoding, structure and semantics of clinical documents for the purpose of exchange. This document can be viewed as human readable format by using \"CDA.xsl\" stylesheet. {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01LPd9C2Y8P5ueev36haTwK9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Ng5gRdnGoeedG5B9QonfKX","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/jmandel/hobby/ehi-export-analysis/results/pulse-systems-inc/ehi-export-report.md","content":"# Pulse Systems, Inc — EHI Export Documentation\n\nCollected: 2026-02-14\n\n## Source\n- Registered URL: https://pulseinc.com/terms-conditions-certification-costs-and-limitations/\n- CHPL IDs: 11500\n- Product: Pulse EHR v8.02\n- Developer: Pulse Systems, Inc (part of Harris Ambulatory Care Enterprise)\n\n## Navigation Journal\n\n### Step 1: Initial probe\n```bash\ncurl -sI -L \"https://pulseinc.com/terms-conditions-certification-costs-and-limitations/\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0'\n```\nHTTP/2 200, Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8. WordPress site on Hostinger/LiteSpeed.\n\n### Step 2: Examine the page\nThe page is titled \"Certification, Costs and Disclosures.\" It contains:\n- ONC certification statement for Pulse EHR v8.0.2 (CHPL ID: 15.04.04.2837.Puls.08.02.1.231206, certified Dec 6, 2023)\n- Full list of certified criteria including 170.315 (b)(10): Electronic Health Information Export\n- Cost disclosures for various features\n- Three documentation links at the bottom\n\n### Step 3: Documentation links found\nThe page has three yellow-colored links at the bottom:\n\n1. **\"View API Documentation\"** → `https://pulseinc.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/63b433c15bacad3a0c435e8c_Pulse_CommonClinicalDataAPI-002.pdf`\n   - A 10-page PDF describing a proprietary REST API for retrieving Common Clinical Data (CCD/CCDA documents). Version 1.0, dated 11/21/2022. Authored by Rob Sprague. This is a custom (non-FHIR) API that uses POST requests, returns base64-encoded XML CCD documents. It requires practice-provided credentials and uses OAuth 2.0.\n\n2. **\"View FHIR API Documentation\"** → `https://harrisambulatory.com/pulse-api-documentation/`\n   - Links to the Harris Ambulatory Care Enterprise page for Pulse's §170.315(g)(10) FHIR API documentation. That page links to a 41-page PDF (`Pulse-8.0-API-FHIR-Documentation.pdf`) describing the FHIR R4 API with US Core profiles. Published endpoint: `https://hag-fhir.amazingcharts.com/pl/endpoints`.\n\n3. **\"View Electronic Health Information Export Documentation\"** → `https://www.hl7.org/fhir/us/core/uscdi.html`\n   - **This link goes to HL7.org's FHIR US Core USCDI page** — an external standards reference, not vendor-specific documentation. This is NOT actual EHI export documentation. Confirmed by navigating in browser and taking a screenshot showing the HL7 FHIR US Core USCDI page.\n\n### Step 4: Checked /certification/ page\n```bash\ncurl -sL \"https://pulseinc.com/certification/\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0'\n```\nThis page contains version 8.0.1 certification info with the same EHI export link pointing to the HL7 USCDI page. No additional EHI export documentation found here.\n\n### Step 5: Broader site search\n- Checked sitemap (`/page-sitemap.xml`): 14 pages total, none related to EHI export documentation.\n- Web search for `site:pulseinc.com \"EHI export\"` found only the certification pages.\n\n### Step 6: External discovery — CHS EHI Export Document\nA web search for `\"Pulse Systems\" OR \"Pulse EHR\" \"EHI export\" documentation` revealed that Community Health Systems (CHS), which deploys Pulse EHR internally, has an EHI export documentation page at `https://www.chs.net/pulse-ehr-information/`.\n\nThat page hosts a Word document: `Pulse-EHI-Export-Document-REV-06142024.docx` (163 KB). This document is branded as \"CHS / CereCore\" and describes the EHI export for Pulse version 16.1 (a different version than the Pulse Systems Inc. v8.02 certified product). However, it provides the only substantive description of how Pulse's EHI export actually works.\n\n```bash\ncurl -sL \"https://www.chs.net/_assets/docs/Pulse-EHI-Export-Document-REV-06142024.docx\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0' -o Pulse-EHI-Export-Document-REV-06142024.docx\n```\n\n## What Was Found\n\n### Pulse Systems' own documentation (at the registered URL)\nThe registered URL provides **no actual EHI export documentation**. The \"View Electronic Health Information Export Documentation\" link redirects to the HL7 FHIR US Core USCDI page — an external standard, not vendor-specific export documentation. There is no data dictionary, no export format specification, no user guide, and no schema describing the (b)(10) export.\n\nThe only relevant content on the page itself is a single sentence under \"Costs and Disclosures\":\n> \"Pulse EHR is certified to data export criteria and can create a set of export summaries in real time. Though the user can create a set of export summaries in real time, this type of mass export is recommended as best practice to be scheduled during off-peak hours to reduce performance stress on the system.\"\n\nThis tells us the export exists and can be run in real time, but provides zero technical detail.\n\n### CHS-hosted EHI Export Document (external, different version)\nThe CHS-hosted `Pulse-EHI-Export-Document-REV-06142024.docx` (created May 2023, revised Sep 2023) describes the export as:\n\n- **Format**: XML document using Clinical Document Architecture (CDA) standard\n- **Mechanism**: \"EHI Tables export\" that generates a computable XML CDA document containing the electronic health information in a patient's Pulse record\n- **Limitations acknowledged**: \"Some electronic health information might not be available in a format, such as rich text documents or images\"\n- **Variability factors**: Content varies based on software applications in use, documentation/use practices, and configuration decisions\n- **Viewer**: CDA.xsl stylesheet from HL7 GitHub for human-readable rendering\n\nThe document lists CDA sections included in the export:\n\n| Section | Included |\n|---------|----------|\n| Security and Privacy Prohibitions | ✓ |\n| Allergies and Adverse Reactions | ✓ |\n| Medications | ✓ |\n| Discharge Medications | ✓ |\n| Problems | ✓ |\n| Hospital Discharge Diagnosis | ✓ |\n| Encounters | ✓ |\n| Admission Diagnosis | ✓ |\n| Procedures | ✓ |\n| Implants | ✓ |\n| Immunizations | ✓ |\n| Vital Signs | ✓ |\n| Social History | ✓ |\n| Results | ✓ |\n| Functional Status | ✓ |\n| Mental Status | ✓ |\n| Assessments | ✓ |\n| Plan of Care | ✓ |\n| Goals Section | ✓ |\n| Health Concerns Section | ✓ |\n| Hospital Discharge Instructions | ✓ |\n| Family History | ✓ |\n| Reason For Visit/Chief Complaint | ✓ |\n| General Status | ✓ |\n| Past Medical History | ✓ |\n| History Of Present Illness | ✓ |\n| Physical Examination | ✓ |\n| Review Of Systems | ✓ |\n| Progress Note | ✓ |\n| PreOperative Diagnosis | ✓ |\n| Postprocedure Diagnosis | ✓ |\n| Planned Procedure | ✓ |\n| Complications | ✓ |\n| Procedure Indications | ✓ |\n| Procedure Description | ✓ |\n| Procedure Note | ✓ |\n| Reason for Referral | ✓ |\n| Hospital Course | ✓ |\n| Health Concerns Section | ✓ |\n| Goals Section | ✓ |\n| Interventions Section | ✓ |\n| Health Status Evaluations/Outcomes Section | ✓ |\n| Discharge Summary Note | ✓ |\n| Consultation Note | ✓ |\n| Payers | ✓ |\n| Financial Data | ✓ |\n\nThe document includes a sample XML CDA fragment at the end, showing the XML structure of the export.\n\n### FHIR API documentation (g)(10), not (b)(10)\nTwo API documents were found:\n1. **Pulse Common Clinical Data API** (10pp PDF): Proprietary REST API for CCD retrieval, not FHIR-based\n2. **Pulse 8.0 API FHIR Documentation** (41pp PDF): Standard FHIR R4/US Core API for (g)(10) compliance. Covers standard US Core resources only (AllergyIntolerance, CarePlan, CareTeam, DocumentReference, Encounter, Goal, Condition, Immunization, DiagnosticReport, Medication, Patient, Procedure, Provenance, Observation, ImplantableDevice, Vital Signs, etc.)\n\nNeither of these constitutes (b)(10) EHI export documentation.\n\n## Export Coverage Assessment\n\n### Data Domain Coverage\nBased on the CHS-hosted document (the only substantive export documentation found), the EHI export uses CDA format which covers a broad range of **clinical** data domains. The section list is extensive — approximately 44 CDA sections covering clinical notes, diagnoses, procedures, medications, allergies, immunizations, vitals, and more.\n\nNotably, the export includes \"Payers\" and \"Financial Data\" sections, which goes beyond the typical clinical-only export. However, based on what the product research tells us Pulse stores, significant data domains are likely missing or inadequately represented:\n\n**Likely covered (based on CDA sections listed):**\n- Patient demographics (implied by CDA header)\n- Clinical notes and encounter documentation\n- Medication lists and prescriptions\n- Laboratory results\n- Vital signs\n- Problem lists and diagnoses\n- Allergies\n- Immunizations\n- Procedures\n- Implantable devices\n- Family history\n- Social history\n- Care plans and goals\n- Payer/insurance data\n- Financial data (section listed but unclear depth)\n\n**Likely missing or uncertain:**\n- **Scheduling and appointment data** — not represented in CDA sections\n- **Billing, claims, and detailed financial data** — \"Financial Data\" section listed but CDA is a clinical document standard; depth of billing/RCM data is highly questionable\n- **Practice management data** — A/R tracking, claims management, denial data, payment posting\n- **Quality measure data** — CQM module data, MIPS/MACRA submissions\n- **Audit logs** — not represented in CDA\n- **Patient portal messages** — InteliChart integration data\n- **Scanned documents, faxes, transcriptions** — document management content\n- **E-prescribing history** — Surescripts transaction logs\n- **Clinical decision support rules** — configuration data\n- **Custom flow sheet data** — \"customizable flow sheets\" are a key Pulse feature; unclear if CDA captures the full custom data structures\n\n### Export Format & Standards\nThe export uses **Clinical Document Architecture (CDA)** — an XML-based HL7 standard for clinical documents. This is a recognized standard, but it's fundamentally a **clinical document exchange format**, not a database export format.\n\nCDA is designed for document exchange between healthcare systems. It excels at representing narrative clinical content with some coded data. However, it is a poor fit for exporting **all** electronic health information from a system that also manages billing, scheduling, practice management, revenue cycle, and population health data. CDA simply cannot represent most of these data domains — there is no CDA section for \"claims denials\" or \"A/R aging\" or \"appointment schedules.\"\n\nThis approach is essentially using the (g)(6) Consolidated CDA export capability to satisfy (b)(10), which is a common vendor shortcut that fails to capture the full breadth of data the system stores.\n\nThe CHS document acknowledges this limitation: \"Some electronic health information might not be available in a format, such as rich text documents or images.\"\n\n### Documentation Quality\n**From Pulse Systems Inc. directly: Essentially nonexistent.** The registered URL's \"View Electronic Health Information Export Documentation\" link points to an external HL7 standards page. There is no vendor-specific data dictionary, no export format specification, no field-level documentation, no user guide, and no sample files hosted by Pulse Systems.\n\n**From CHS (external, different version):** The document is brief (6 pages including cover page and table of contents). It provides a useful list of CDA sections and a sample XML snippet, but lacks:\n- Field-level definitions within each section\n- Data types, value sets, or constraints\n- Instructions for performing the export\n- Explanation of how non-clinical data is handled\n- Description of completeness relative to what the system stores\n\nA developer receiving this export would know it's a CDA XML document and could identify the sections, but would need to rely entirely on the CDA standard itself for parsing — which is reasonable for a standards-based format. However, the documentation provides no guidance on Pulse-specific extensions, limitations, or data mapping.\n\n### Structure & Completeness\n- **Granularity**: Section-level only (lists CDA section names). No field-level documentation.\n- **Value sets**: Not documented (defers to CDA standard).\n- **Relationships**: Not documented (inherent in CDA structure).\n- **Versioning**: Document dated May/Sep 2023; no change history.\n- **Sample data**: One partial XML snippet included.\n\n### Overall Assessment\nThis is one of the weakest (b)(10) implementations encountered. The vendor (Pulse Systems Inc.) has registered a mandatory disclosures URL that contains a \"View Electronic Health Information Export Documentation\" link pointing to an external HL7 standards page — not their own documentation. This is not a documentation oversight; it fundamentally misrepresents what the link leads to.\n\nThe only actual EHI export documentation for Pulse was found on a third-party site (CHS/CereCore) for a different product version (16.1 vs 8.02). That document reveals the export is a CDA XML document — a clinical document standard being used as a (b)(10) export mechanism. While CDA covers clinical data reasonably well, it cannot represent the scheduling, billing, practice management, revenue cycle, quality reporting, and administrative data that Pulse EHR stores and that (b)(10) is intended to capture.\n\nThe vendor appears to have conflated (b)(10) with clinical document exchange, pointing to USCDI/US Core (which is the (g)(10) domain) as their EHI export documentation. This suggests a fundamental misunderstanding of the (b)(10) requirement — or a deliberate decision to satisfy it minimally with existing clinical document capabilities rather than building a true comprehensive export.\n\n## Access Summary\n- Final URL (after redirects): https://pulseinc.com/terms-conditions-certification-costs-and-limitations/\n- Status: found\n- Required browser: no (page is static HTML, no JS required for content)\n- Navigation complexity: direct_link (links are visible at bottom of page)\n- Anti-bot issues: none\n\n## Obstacles & Dead Ends\n1. The \"View Electronic Health Information Export Documentation\" link on both the registered URL and `/certification/` pages points to `https://www.hl7.org/fhir/us/core/uscdi.html` — an external HL7 standards page, not vendor documentation.\n2. No EHI export documentation found anywhere on pulseinc.com (checked sitemap, all pages).\n3. No EHI export documentation found on harrisambulatory.com (only FHIR API docs).\n4. The CHS-hosted document (`Pulse-EHI-Export-Document-REV-06142024.docx`) is for Pulse v16.1, which appears to be a different version line than the Pulse Systems v8.02 certified product. CHS uses Pulse internally and may have a customized deployment, so the export behavior described may not exactly match the Pulse Systems product.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":797,"cache_read_input_tokens":105307,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":797},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d65e0b77-4a97-43d8-b0ff-f4d1956a9a56","uuid":"88032c45-7b00-46dd-a75c-1b74f51399ef"}

WordPress site on Hostinger/LiteSpeed.\n\n### Step 2: Examine the page\nThe page is titled \"Certification, Costs and Disclosures.\" It contains:\n- ONC certification statement for Pulse EHR v8.0.2 (CHPL ID: 15.04.04.2837.Puls.08.02.1.231206, certified Dec 6, 2023)\n- Full list of certified criteria including 170.315 (b)(10): Electronic Health Information Export\n- Cost disclosures for various features\n- Three documentation links at the bottom\n\n### Step 3: Documentation links found\nThe page has three yellow-colored links at the bottom:\n\n1. **\"View API Documentation\"** → `https://pulseinc.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/63b433c15bacad3a0c435e8c_Pulse_CommonClinicalDataAPI-002.pdf`\n   - A 10-page PDF describing a proprietary REST API for retrieving Common Clinical Data (CCD/CCDA documents). Version 1.0, dated 11/21/2022. Authored by Rob Sprague. This is a custom (non-FHIR) API that uses POST requests, returns base64-encoded XML CCD documents. It requires practice-provided credentials and uses OAuth 2.0.\n\n2. **\"View FHIR API Documentation\"** → `https://harrisambulatory.com/pulse-api-documentation/`\n   - Links to the Harris Ambulatory Care Enterprise page for Pulse's §170.315(g)(10) FHIR API documentation. That page links to a 41-page PDF (`Pulse-8.0-API-FHIR-Documentation.pdf`) describing the FHIR R4 API with US Core profiles. Published endpoint: `https://hag-fhir.amazingcharts.com/pl/endpoints`.\n\n3. **\"View Electronic Health Information Export Documentation\"** → `https://www.hl7.org/fhir/us/core/uscdi.html`\n   - **This link goes to HL7.org's FHIR US Core USCDI page** — an external standards reference, not vendor-specific documentation. This is NOT actual EHI export documentation. Confirmed by navigating in browser and taking a screenshot showing the HL7 FHIR US Core USCDI page.\n\n### Step 4: Checked /certification/ page\n```bash\ncurl -sL \"https://pulseinc.com/certification/\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0'\n```\nThis page contains version 8.0.1 certification info with the same EHI export link pointing to the HL7 USCDI page. No additional EHI export documentation found here.\n\n### Step 5: Broader site search\n- Checked sitemap (`/page-sitemap.xml`): 14 pages total, none related to EHI export documentation.\n- Web search for `site:pulseinc.com \"EHI export\"` found only the certification pages.\n\n### Step 6: External discovery — CHS EHI Export Document\nA web search for `\"Pulse Systems\" OR \"Pulse EHR\" \"EHI export\" documentation` revealed that Community Health Systems (CHS), which deploys Pulse EHR internally, has an EHI export documentation page at `https://www.chs.net/pulse-ehr-information/`.\n\nThat page hosts a Word document: `Pulse-EHI-Export-Document-REV-06142024.docx` (163 KB). This document is branded as \"CHS / CereCore\" and describes the EHI export for Pulse version 16.1 (a different version than the Pulse Systems Inc. v8.02 certified product). However, it provides the only substantive description of how Pulse's EHI export actually works.\n\n```bash\ncurl -sL \"https://www.chs.net/_assets/docs/Pulse-EHI-Export-Document-REV-06142024.docx\" -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0' -o Pulse-EHI-Export-Document-REV-06142024.docx\n```\n\n## What Was Found\n\n### Pulse Systems' own documentation (at the registered URL)\nThe registered URL provides **no actual EHI export documentation**. The \"View Electronic Health Information Export Documentation\" link redirects to the HL7 FHIR US Core USCDI page — an external standard, not vendor-specific export documentation. There is no data dictionary, no export format specification, no user guide, and no schema describing the (b)(10) export.\n\nThe only relevant content on the page itself is a single sentence under \"Costs and Disclosures\":\n> \"Pulse EHR is certified to data export criteria and can create a set of export summaries in real time. Though the user can create a set of export summaries in real time, this type of mass export is recommended as best practice to be scheduled during off-peak hours to reduce performance stress on the system.\"\n\nThis tells us the export exists and can be run in real time, but provides zero technical detail.\n\n### CHS-hosted EHI Export Document (external, different version)\nThe CHS-hosted `Pulse-EHI-Export-Document-REV-06142024.docx` (created May 2023, revised Sep 2023) describes the export as:\n\n- **Format**: XML document using Clinical Document Architecture (CDA) standard\n- **Mechanism**: \"EHI Tables export\" that generates a computable XML CDA document containing the electronic health information in a patient's Pulse record\n- **Limitations acknowledged**: \"Some electronic health information might not be available in a format, such as rich text documents or images\"\n- **Variability factors**: Content varies based on software applications in use, documentation/use practices, and configuration decisions\n- **Viewer**: CDA.xsl stylesheet from HL7 GitHub for human-readable rendering\n\nThe document lists CDA sections included in the export:\n\n| Section | Included |\n|---------|----------|\n| Security and Privacy Prohibitions | ✓ |\n| Allergies and Adverse Reactions | ✓ |\n| Medications | ✓ |\n| Discharge Medications | ✓ |\n| Problems | ✓ |\n| Hospital Discharge Diagnosis | ✓ |\n| Encounters | ✓ |\n| Admission Diagnosis | ✓ |\n| Procedures | ✓ |\n| Implants | ✓ |\n| Immunizations | ✓ |\n| Vital Signs | ✓ |\n| Social History | ✓ |\n| Results | ✓ |\n| Functional Status | ✓ |\n| Mental Status | ✓ |\n| Assessments | ✓ |\n| Plan of Care | ✓ |\n| Goals Section | ✓ |\n| Health Concerns Section | ✓ |\n| Hospital Discharge Instructions | ✓ |\n| Family History | ✓ |\n| Reason For Visit/Chief Complaint | ✓ |\n| General Status | ✓ |\n| Past Medical History | ✓ |\n| History Of Present Illness | ✓ |\n| Physical Examination | ✓ |\n| Review Of Systems | ✓ |\n| Progress Note | ✓ |\n| PreOperative Diagnosis | ✓ |\n| Postprocedure Diagnosis | ✓ |\n| Planned Procedure | ✓ |\n| Complications | ✓ |\n| Procedure Indications | ✓ |\n| Procedure Description | ✓ |\n| Procedure Note | ✓ |\n| Reason for Referral | ✓ |\n| Hospital Course | ✓ |\n| Health Concerns Section | ✓ |\n| Goals Section | ✓ |\n| Interventions Section | ✓ |\n| Health Status Evaluations/Outcomes Section | ✓ |\n| Discharge Summary Note | ✓ |\n| Consultation Note | ✓ |\n| Payers | ✓ |\n| Financial Data | ✓ |\n\nThe document includes a sample XML CDA fragment at the end, showing the XML structure of the export.\n\n### FHIR API documentation (g)(10), not (b)(10)\nTwo API documents were found:\n1. **Pulse Common Clinical Data API** (10pp PDF): Proprietary REST API for CCD retrieval, not FHIR-based\n2. **Pulse 8.0 API FHIR Documentation** (41pp PDF): Standard FHIR R4/US Core API for (g)(10) compliance. Covers standard US Core resources only (AllergyIntolerance, CarePlan, CareTeam, DocumentReference, Encounter, Goal, Condition, Immunization, DiagnosticReport, Medication, Patient, Procedure, Provenance, Observation, ImplantableDevice, Vital Signs, etc.)\n\nNeither of these constitutes (b)(10) EHI export documentation.\n\n## Export Coverage Assessment\n\n### Data Domain Coverage\nBased on the CHS-hosted document (the only substantive export documentation found), the EHI export uses CDA format which covers a broad range of **clinical** data domains. The section list is extensive — approximately 44 CDA sections covering clinical notes, diagnoses, procedures, medications, allergies, immunizations, vitals, and more.\n\nNotably, the export includes \"Payers\" and \"Financial Data\" sections, which goes beyond the typical clinical-only export. However, based on what the product research tells us Pulse stores, significant data domains are likely missing or inadequately represented:\n\n**Likely covered (based on CDA sections listed):**\n- Patient demographics (implied by CDA header)\n- Clinical notes and encounter documentation\n- Medication lists and prescriptions\n- Laboratory results\n- Vital signs\n- Problem lists and diagnoses\n- Allergies\n- Immunizations\n- Procedures\n- Implantable devices\n- Family history\n- Social history\n- Care plans and goals\n- Payer/insurance data\n- Financial data (section listed but unclear depth)\n\n**Likely missing or uncertain:**\n- **Scheduling and appointment data** — not represented in CDA sections\n- **Billing, claims, and detailed financial data** — \"Financial Data\" section listed but CDA is a clinical document standard; depth of billing/RCM data is highly questionable\n- **Practice management data** — A/R tracking, claims management, denial data, payment posting\n- **Quality measure data** — CQM module data, MIPS/MACRA submissions\n- **Audit logs** — not represented in CDA\n- **Patient portal messages** — InteliChart integration data\n- **Scanned documents, faxes, transcriptions** — document management content\n- **E-prescribing history** — Surescripts transaction logs\n- **Clinical decision support rules** — configuration data\n- **Custom flow sheet data** — \"customizable flow sheets\" are a key Pulse feature; unclear if CDA captures the full custom data structures\n\n### Export Format & Standards\nThe export uses **Clinical Document Architecture (CDA)** — an XML-based HL7 standard for clinical documents. This is a recognized standard, but it's fundamentally a **clinical document exchange format**, not a database export format.\n\nCDA is designed for document exchange between healthcare systems. It excels at representing narrative clinical content with some coded data. However, it is a poor fit for exporting **all** electronic health information from a system that also manages billing, scheduling, practice management, revenue cycle, and population health data. CDA simply cannot represent most of these data domains — there is no CDA section for \"claims denials\" or \"A/R aging\" or \"appointment schedules.\"\n\nThis approach is essentially using the (g)(6) Consolidated CDA export capability to satisfy (b)(10), which is a common vendor shortcut that fails to capture the full breadth of data the system stores.\n\nThe CHS document acknowledges this limitation: \"Some electronic health information might not be available in a format, such as rich text documents or images.\"\n\n### Documentation Quality\n**From Pulse Systems Inc. directly: Essentially nonexistent.** The registered URL's \"View Electronic Health Information Export Documentation\" link points to an external HL7 standards page. There is no vendor-specific data dictionary, no export format specification, no field-level documentation, no user guide, and no sample files hosted by Pulse Systems.\n\n**From CHS (external, different version):** The document is brief (6 pages including cover page and table of contents). It provides a useful list of CDA sections and a sample XML snippet, but lacks:\n- Field-level definitions within each section\n- Data types, value sets, or constraints\n- Instructions for performing the export\n- Explanation of how non-clinical data is handled\n- Description of completeness relative to what the system stores\n\nA developer receiving this export would know it's a CDA XML document and could identify the sections, but would need to rely entirely on the CDA standard itself for parsing — which is reasonable for a standards-based format. However, the documentation provides no guidance on Pulse-specific extensions, limitations, or data mapping.\n\n### Structure & Completeness\n- **Granularity**: Section-level only (lists CDA section names). No field-level documentation.\n- **Value sets**: Not documented (defers to CDA standard).\n- **Relationships**: Not documented (inherent in CDA structure).\n- **Versioning**: Document dated May/Sep 2023; no change history.\n- **Sample data**: One partial XML snippet included.\n\n### Overall Assessment\nThis is one of the weakest (b)(10) implementations encountered. The vendor (Pulse Systems Inc.) has registered a mandatory disclosures URL that contains a \"View Electronic Health Information Export Documentation\" link pointing to an external HL7 standards page — not their own documentation. This is not a documentation oversight; it fundamentally misrepresents what the link leads to.\n\nThe only actual EHI export documentation for Pulse was found on a third-party site (CHS/CereCore) for a different product version (16.1 vs 8.02). That document reveals the export is a CDA XML document — a clinical document standard being used as a (b)(10) export mechanism. While CDA covers clinical data reasonably well, it cannot represent the scheduling, billing, practice management, revenue cycle, quality reporting, and administrative data that Pulse EHR stores and that (b)(10) is intended to capture.\n\nThe vendor appears to have conflated (b)(10) with clinical document exchange, pointing to USCDI/US Core (which is the (g)(10) domain) as their EHI export documentation.
